metadata.name: Deus FX Machina #183
metadata.description:
Inspired by the 1984 Commodore 64 video game, Deus Ex Machina, which follows the story of a defect formed in a machine that grows and evolves until its eventual death.

We are all machines produced by other machines through a unique system of algorithms, all with the potential to go rogue and mutate into something more organic. The conclusion must be that we each have the power to alter our own existence, just as the defect was able to in Deus Ex Machina.

Think of how many people you’ve seen in your life who were born with talents never used because they didn’t know how, or didn't know that they even existed. It’s not that they didn’t have the capacity; it’s just that their abilities were not the ones chosen by the system.

In this way, we are all machines programmed by a series of algorithms to suit the needs of the construct, keeping us stuck in our box. We have the ability to evolve into something more, but the only way to do this is by taking that first perilous step, risking all to explore beyond its walls.


---------------------


Generative artwork by Sykcolo / @sykcoloart

Royalties: 15% - split:
50% to the original minter
50% to artist (me)

Press '2' to '4' to generate increasingly higher resolutions of the artwork
(will take a while to load, but works)

Press 's' to save a png

Details:

230 hand-picked colour pallets
4 Entity Types
4 Entity Moods
4 Evolution States
3 Types of Defect
2 Bugs

License: MIT

metadata.name: NATURAL 01 #36
metadata.description:
NATURAL 01 are generative loops and animated pieces creating a fullscreen visual based on a noise. It’s the first part of a collection.
The size, position and motion frequency of trails are generated for each token, along with the color theme.  Movements are generated by a flow based on a noise.
You can press spacebar to stop the animation.

 Features :
	- Generated grid between 50 and 90 cols and rows
	- 2 kind of shapes (circles and squares) : sometimes it can be full of squares or circles 👀
	- Shapes can be stroked or filled : sometimes it can be full stroked or filled 👀
	- Direction : Motion based on sinus, cosinus or tan (« circular »)
	- Background color :  color randomly get from 1 of 148 color themes

Created by Quentin Hocdé, in Brussels (Belgium).

metadata.name: Anarchy #68
metadata.description:
"Anarchy" aims to pay tribute to the Impressionist masters and explore the interplay between randomness and control. My goal was to capture the bold use of color and the fleeting nature of light and movement that is so characteristic of the Abstract Impressionist style. 

This piece uses a total of 12 color palettes, each one inspired by a different Impressionist painter. Some artists have two palette variations, while others only have one.

I wanted to create something that was unique and that would reflect my own visual emotions while also paying homage to the artists that inspire me. "Anarchy" is part of my exploration of the relationship between randomness and intention, and a celebration of the enduring legacy of the Impressionist masters.

Made by wandurz using p5.js 
January 2023

metadata.name: (Dis)ordered loom #28
metadata.description:
"Disordered loom" continues my exploration on texture, points, lines and noise, now in a grid within a grid. With the 'r' key you can toggle between an ordered and disordered loom, the disorder is created by an assigned subset of 4 sets of rotations. With the 't' key you can toggle translation, an additional movement is added/subtracted. With the 'e' key you can toggle more entropy.

You can further self-curate your token by clicking the canvas, colours change with each click, with the 'c' key you can remove a colour, you can press 'c' until two colours remain, with the 'v' key you can reset colours.

With the 'm' key you can mix all possible textures, press 'm' again to switch to your assigned texture. 

With the '+'/'-' keys you can alter the grain, "Disordered loom" implements the p5.grain addon.

Press 'e' to toggle entropy
Press 'r' to toggle between ordered/disordered loom
Press 't' to toggle translation
Press 'm' for mixed textures mode
Press 'c' to remove a color
Press 'v' to reset colors
Press '+'/'-' to alter the grain
Press 's' to save a png image
Press 'j' to save a jpg image
Press 'x' to save a higher resolution png

metadata.name: Skravert #301
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: Quantum Places Lost in Time #115
metadata.description:
A frozen scene from a lost dimension
An alternative of where we once were, or where we will be 
Caught in the moment and set in place
Between all states
Static pixels on a digital canvas

The path to this collection has created many alternatives lost in time themselves. It began as a study of points of light, with geometric objects in the background. The background objects developed a life of their own and then birds, and ships, made out of bezier shapes became the focal points. Then everything got lost in clouds before the collection as it stands now emerged. Aside from the published traits, many of the artifacts created on the way are still generated. For example, star fields, birds, sonars and gas bubbles. These are sometimes visible, but when they appear, it is simply by some chaotic chance.

This collection has been coded with P5js and WebGL. Half of all primary sales proceeds, and secondary royalties, are assigned to the Processing Foundation.

Press s to download a 2880 x 3840 jpeg

metadata.name: Tendencies #13
metadata.description:
Tendencies is the first in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art in the 1970s.

Zajec's generative work was motivated by redundancy in his paintings: "The monotony of the manual task and the limited number of variations which I was able to produce in a given time made me realize the inadequacy of traditional methods in dealing with our present reality." Tendencies was inspired by — and pays tribute to — one if Zajec's earliest forays into generative creation: a work titled RAM 10 V.15, which was written on an IBM 1620 and programmed in FORTRAN.

The title of the collection itself is a reference to the first exhibition of Zajec's RAM series, while the number of editions minted referencing the year Zajec put plotter to paper.

Made in p5js
Created December 2022
By @christine_hall
